  "forensic": {
    "category": "audio",
    "riskLevel": "low",
    "suspiciousPatterns": [
      {
        "name": "Byte-swapped DTS (SPDIF transport)",
        "condition": "dtsSyncWord == 4272742400",
        "severity": "info",
        "description": "DTS sync word matches the 16-bit little-endian byte-swapped format (0xFE7F0180) used for SPDIF/AES3 digital audio transport. This file may be extracted directly from a SPDIF/IEC 60958 stream rather than stored as raw DTS Core."
      }
    ]
  },
  "aiHints": {
    "analysisContext": "DTS Core frame structure (all BE): sync_word(4,BE,=0x7FFE8001) + header_word_1(4,BE: bits 31=FTYPE/30-26=SHORT/25=CPF/24-18=NBLKS/17-4=FSIZE). FSIZE is a 14-bit field spanning two words — actual frame size in bytes = FSIZE + 1. AMODE (audio channel arrangement): 0=mono, 1=dual-mono, 2=stereo, 3=sum-diff, 9=5.1. SFREQ (sample rate): 1=8kHz/6=22.05kHz/7=24kHz/8=32kHz/11=44.1kHz/12=48kHz/13=96kHz/14=192kHz. RATE (bitrate): 0=32kbps/5=96kbps/14=768kbps/15=open/16=variable. DTS-HD extension: look for DTS-HD Master Audio sync word 0x64582025 after the DTS Core frame in .dtshd files. DTS frames are variable length (95-32640 bytes).",
    "suggestedInspections": [
      "Verify sync word at offset 0: 7F FE 80 01 (big-endian DTS Core)",
      "Check for byte-swapped sync (SPDIF): FE 7F 01 80",
      "Extract AMODE bits from header to determine channel layout (stereo=2, 5.1=9)",
      "Extract SFREQ bits for sample rate (common: 11=44.1kHz, 12=48kHz, 13=96kHz)",
      "For .dtshd files: scan for DTS-HD extension substream after the Core frames"
    ]
  },
  "software": [
    "VLC media player",
